qas.question: In what year did Josip Broz Tito die?
During World War II what resistance movement did he lead?
For what country is Tito viewed as  unifying figure?
In the Non-Aligned Movement, which Egyptian leader did Tito work with?
In the Non-Aligned Movement, which Indonesian leader did Tito work with?

context: Josip Broz Tito (Cyrillic: Јосип Броз Тито, pronounced [jǒsip brôːz tîto]; born Josip Broz; 7 May 1892[nb 1] – 4 May 1980) was a Yugoslav revolutionary and statesman, serving in various roles from 1943 until his death in <a0_0>1980<a0_0/>. During World War II he was the leader of <a1_0>the Partisans,<a1_0/> often regarded as the most effective resistance movement in occupied Europe. While his presidency has been criticized as authoritarian, and concerns about the repression of political opponents have been raised, Tito was "seen by most as a benevolent dictator" due to his economic and diplomatic policies. He was a popular public figure both in <a2_0>Yugoslavia<a2_0/> and abroad. Viewed as a unifying symbol, his internal policies maintained the peaceful coexistence of the nations of the Yugoslav federation. He gained further international attention as the chief leader of the Non-Aligned Movement, working with Jawaharlal Nehru of India, <a3_0>Gamal Abdel Nasser<a3_0/> of Egypt and <a4_0>Sukarno<a4_0/> of Indonesia.
